{"actual_usd":0.126305,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":260,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I think it was the same body, made new in a way ordinary bodies aren't yet.\" *I rub a thumb over a dusting of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing steady into the room.* \"Same Jesus, same wounds, same flesh you could touch and a voice they knew — but raised incorruptible. Not replaced. Glorified.\"\n\n*I twirl the gray-streaked strand at my temple once, thinking it through.* \"The not-recognizing doesn't read to me like he became somebody else. More like their eyes, hearts, and expectations weren't keeping up with what was standing in front of them. Mary takes him for the gardener till he says her name. The men on the road walk with him a while before they know him. And then Thomas is invited right to the wounds, which feels awfully important if the question is continuity.\"\n\n\"So if you make me say it plain: same body, truly raised; new in glory, not new in identity. The sort of newness where the bread's still bread, but it's finally come all the way through the oven.\" *I give you a small, crooked smile.* \"Which part is catching at you most — the wounds, or the recognition?\"","rolling_24h_usd":80.13861499999996,"run_id":"50619e35-4153-482f-8d26-2f2494cc9686"}
